Exosomes, as natural occurring vesicles, play highly important roles in the 
behavior and fate of ischemic diseases and different tumors. Secretion, 
composition, and function of exosomes are remarkably influenced by hypoxia in 
ischemic diseases and tumor microenvironment. Exosomes secreted from hypoxic 
cells affect development, growth, angiogenesis, and progression in ischemic 
diseases and tumors through a variety of signaling pathways. In this review 
article, we discuss how hypoxia affects the quantity and quality of exosomes, 
and review the mechanisms by which hypoxic cell-derived exosomes regulate 
ischemic cell behaviors in both cancerous and noncancerous cells.

